            , was indicted for <rs id="t17841020-55-off254" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-off254" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-off254" type="offenceSubcategory" value="grandLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the 1st of October, one carpet, called a Bengal carpet, value 10 s.
            </rs> the property of 
               
                  <persName id="t17841020-55-victim558" type="victimName">
                     Edward 
                     Torrie
                  <interp inst="t17841020-55-victim558" type="surname" value="Torrie"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-victim558" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-victim558" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t17841020-55-off254 t17841020-55-victim558"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17841020-55-person559">
                  EDWARD
                   TORRIE
               <interp inst="t17841020-55-person559" type="surname" value="TORRIE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-person559" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-person559" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>On my return to my lodgings, about seven in the evening, I was informed I had lost two bedside carpets; I went to Justice Walker's, where the prisoner was in custody, and the two carpets, and I swore to one carpet; I left my apartment open, they were there when I went out.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17841020-55-person560">
                  JAMES
                   DENNISON
               <interp inst="t17841020-55-person560" type="surname" value="DENNISON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-person560" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-person560" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I was in my shop, adjoining to the house where the prosecutor lodges; I saw a man<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178410200093"></xptr> go up the stairs, I thought he was a thief; I went round and saw a man come out of the house and give the prisoner some carpets; the prisoner was about two or three yards from the door; when the prisoner began to go away I laid hold of him, he dropped a carpet, a young man saw him, and he was taken into custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17841020-55-person561">
                  JOHN
                   HILL
               <interp inst="t17841020-55-person561" type="surname" value="HILL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-person561" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17841020-55-person561" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I saw a man come up and down stairs two or three times, and the last witness and me went round, and saw a man come out with a carpet under his arm, and give it to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>(The carpet deposed to.)</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>A gentleman offered me sixpence to carry it.</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. The prisoner first said he found it at the door, and did not know it belonged to any body.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17841020-55-verdict255" type="verdictDescription">
